Duration: 8 Hours

CONNECTING REACT TO SPRING BOOT:

  // Spring Boot — enable CORS for frontend
  @CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:5173")  // Vite dev server
  @RestController
  public class UserController { ... }

  // Or globally
  @Configuration
  public class CorsConfig implements WebMvcConfigurer {
    public void addCorsMappings(CorsRegistry registry) {
      registry.addMapping("/api/**")
        .allowedOrigins("http://localhost:5173")
        .allowedMethods("GET","POST","PUT","DELETE")
        .allowCredentials(true);
    }
  }

REST API CONSUMPTION IN REACT:
  // useEffect + axios in a React component
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  useEffect(() => {
    axios.get('http://localhost:8080/api/users')
      .then(res => setUsers(res.data))
      .catch(err => console.error(err));
  }, []);

STATE MANAGEMENT ACROSS FULL STACK:
  Client state: React useState/Context/Redux
  Server state: React Query or SWR (automatic caching, refetching, invalidation)
    const { data, isLoading } = useQuery(['users'], () => axios.get('/api/users'))

DATA FLOW & ERROR HANDLING:
  React → Axios → Spring Boot Controller → Service → Repository → DB
  Error flows back: DB error → Spring exception → @RestControllerAdvice → JSON error response → Axios catch → React UI error state

